Goal

The goal of this project is to build an end-to-end web application to implement, configure and evaluate recommender systems using different approaches. To achieve this, the assignment calls for using a user-item ratings dataset (from MovieLens in this case) and implement two recommendation algorithms:

    - Recommendations by Movie Genres
    
    - Recommendations by Collaborative Filtering Algorithm

The evaluation should compare these approaches based on their accuracy using normalization techniques, similarity methods, neighborhood sizes, etc.

Reading Data

 myurl = "https://liangfgithub.github.io/MovieData/"

Ratings Data All ratings are contained in the file “ratings.dat” and are in the following format:

UserID::MovieID::Rating::Timestamp

  • UserIDs range between 1 and 6040
  • MovieID ranges from 1 to 3952, but not all of them are included in movies. Further, 177 movies are in movies but not rated in ratings.
  • Ratings are made on a 5-star scale
  • Timestamp is represented in seconds
ratings = read.csv(paste0(myurl, 'ratings.dat?raw=true'), 
                   sep = ':',
                   colClasses = c('integer', 'NULL'), 
                   header = FALSE)
colnames(ratings) = c('UserID', 'MovieID', 'Rating', 'Timestamp')

Movies Data Movie information is in the file “movies.dat” and is in the following format:

MovieID::Title::Genres

  • Movie Titles are similar to the titles provided by IMDB
  • Genres from the file are : “Action”, “Adventure”, “Animation”, “Children’s”, “Comedy”, “Crime”, “Documentary”, “Drama”, “Fantasy”, “Film-Noir”, “Horror”, “Musical”, “Mystery”, “Romance”, “Sci-Fi”, “Thriller”, “War”, “Western”
  • In movies.dat, some movie names contain single colon (:), so the method above does not work.

System 1: Recommendation of Movie By Genre

System 1 gives the recommendation of movies by their genres. Users are given an option to select the genre of their choice and top 5 movies are recommended. Two different approaches were tried to give the recommendations. Approach 1 given below, displays the movie recommendations based on the popularity.

Approach 1: Recommendation based on popularity

  • MovieIDs with Ratings greater than 2 out of 5 are filtered and grouped based on their genres. That for a movie to be recommended, it should have atleast some rating (here 2/5) from each genre to be shortlisted.
  • Top 5 Movies with higher individual ratings obtained from the above condition are recommended to the user.
popular_genre = function(gfrominput)
{
  genre = ratings %>%
    group_by(MovieID) %>%
    summarize(ratings_per_movie = sum(Rating > 2)) %>%
    inner_join(movies, by = 'MovieID') %>%
    group_by(Genres) %>%
    arrange(desc = ratings_per_movie)
  genre = genre[grepl(gfrominput, genre$Genres, fixed = TRUE),]
  nr = nrow(genre)
  low = nr-5+1
  return(genre[nr:low,])
}

Recommendations of System 1: Approach 1

Approach 2: Recommendation based on Movie Ratings

  • Average rating for each movie is calculated and grouped by genre.
  • Movies that have atleast 1000 ratings are then filtered and top 5 out of these filtered movies are presented to the user.
popular_genre = function(gfrominput)
{
  genre = ratings %>%
    group_by(MovieID) %>%
    summarize(ratings_per_movie = n(), ave_ratings = mean(Rating)) %>%
    inner_join(movies, by = 'MovieID') %>%
    group_by(Genres) %>%
    filter(ratings_per_movie > 1000) %>%
    top_n(5, ave_ratings)
  genre = genre[grepl(gfrominput, genre$Genres, fixed = TRUE),]
  return(genre)
}

We can observe that different movies are recommended by two different approaches. We decided to go approach 1 for system 1, which is recommending movies by popularity.

System 2: Collaborative Recommendation System

Two collaborative recommendation algorithms namely UBCF (User-Based Collaborative Filtering) and IBCF (Item-based Collaborative Filtering).

Approach 1: User-Based Collaborative Filtering

  • Based on the given input, we try to find the most similar users
  • Cosine similarity is used to find the most similar users and select the one that takes least time.
  • Based on similar users, we try to predict the movie ratings by taking the average of ratings given by these similar users. Weights are assigned to the predictions that have similarity
library(recommenderlab)
myurl = "https://liangfgithub.github.io/MovieData/"
ratings = read.csv(paste0(myurl, 'ratings.dat?raw=true'),
                   sep = ':',
                   colClasses = c('integer', 'NULL'),
                   header = FALSE)
colnames(ratings) = c('UserID', 'MovieID', 'Rating', 'Timestamp')
i = paste0('u', ratings$UserID)
j = paste0('m', ratings$MovieID)
x = ratings$Rating
tmp = data.frame(i, j, x, stringsAsFactors = T)
Rmat = sparseMatrix(as.integer(tmp$i), as.integer(tmp$j), x = tmp$x)
rownames(Rmat) = levels(tmp$i)
colnames(Rmat) = levels(tmp$j)
Rmat = new('realRatingMatrix', data = Rmat)

train = Rmat[1:500, ]
test = Rmat[501, ]

A sparse matrix is created by m x n dimenions, m = the total no of users and n = the total no of movies. For instance, element at [1,1] represents the rating given by user_1 for movie_1

data = as(train, "matrix")
user.means = rowMeans(data, na.rm = TRUE)
data = data - user.means

newdata = as(test, "matrix")
newuser.mean = mean(newdata, na.rm = TRUE)
newdata = newdata - newuser.mean

sim = rep(0, dim(data)[1])
for(i in 1:length(sim))
{
tmp.y = as.vector(newdata)
ind.y = which(!is.na(tmp.y))
tmp.x = data[i, ]
ind.x = which(!is.na(tmp.x))
ind = intersect(ind.x, ind.y)
if (length(ind) > 0){
tmp.x = tmp.x[ind]
tmp.y = tmp.y[ind]
sim[i] = sum(tmp.x * tmp.y) / sqrt(sum(tmp.x^2) * sum(tmp.y^2))
}
}
sim = (1 + sim)/2

k = 20

idx = order(sim, decreasing = TRUE)[1:k]
sim[-idx]=0

mypred = colSums(data*sim, na.rm=TRUE)/colSums( (!is.na(data)) * sim )
mypred[!is.na(newdata)]= NA
mypred[is.nan(mypred)] = NA
mypred = mypred + newuser.mean

The above code represents the UBCF alogrithm without using Recommenderlab function.

recommender.UBCF <- Recommender(train, method = "UBCF",
                                parameter = list(normalize = 'center',
                                                 method = 'Cosine',
                                                 nn = 20))

p.UBCF <- predict(recommender.UBCF, test, type="ratings")
p.UBCF <- as.numeric(as(p.UBCF, "matrix"))

sum(is.na(p.UBCF) != is.na(mypred)) ### should be zero
## [1] 0
max(abs(p.UBCF - mypred), na.rm = TRUE)  ### should be less than 1e-06
## [1] 4.953572e-07

The predictions produced by the model we wrote are close enough to the predictions made by the Recommenderlab function. Thereby achieving the target benchmark set.

To explain more about the functioning of this approach, we are normalize because Some users give practically all movies high ratings, while others give very low ratings. By removing the mean rating for each user, we can equalize the user ratings and eliminate the impact of user preferences. The nearest neighborhood considered here is 30 and cosine similarity is used to identify the similar UserIDs.

Approach 2: Item-based Collaborative Filtering

This approach also has a similar steps as that of UBCF. But here, a correlation matrix is built between all the movies. Based on the user rating for a particular movie, a highly correlated movie is suggested fromt this large sparse matrix m x m, where m is the total no. of movies. This sparse matrix is built by using the cosine similarity.

data = as(train, "matrix")
user.means = rowMeans(data, na.rm = TRUE)
data = data - user.means

newdata = as(test, "matrix")


sim1 = proxy::simil(data, method = "cosine", by_rows = F)
sim1 = (1 + sim1)/2

sim1 = as.matrix(sim1)

for(i in 1:ncol(data)){
  similar_items = tail(order(sim1[i,], decreasing = FALSE, na.last = FALSE), 30)
  sim1[i, -similar_items]= NA
}
ra = as.vector(newdata)
ra_mat = matrix(rep(ra, each = 3706), nrow = 3706)
data12 = sim1 * ra_mat

non_na_vec = which(is.na(newdata))
mypred = rep(NA, times = ncol(newdata))

for (i in 1:length(non_na_vec)){
  num = sum(data12[non_na_vec[i],], na.rm =T)
  den = sum(!is.na(data12[non_na_vec[i],]))
  mypred[non_na_vec[i]] = num/den
}

mypred[is.infinite(mypred)] = NA
mypred[is.nan(mypred)] = NA
recommender.IBCF <- Recommender(train, method = "IBCF",
                                parameter = list(normalize = 'center',
                                                 method = 'Cosine',
                                                 k = 30))

p.IBCF <- predict(recommender.IBCF, test, type="ratings")
p.IBCF <- as.numeric(as(p.IBCF, "matrix"))

## first output: should be less than 10
sum(is.na(p.IBCF) != is.na(mypred))
## [1] 1
## second output: should be less than 10%
mydiff = abs(p.IBCF - mypred)
sum(mydiff[!is.na(mydiff)] > 1e-6) / sum(!is.na(mydiff))
## [1] 0.0880829

This approach has also passed the target benchmark set by the professor.

We deployed an IBCF recommendation system as part for System 2. This is because, the majority of the work is done during training (including sorting and computing the item-to-item M-by-M similarity matrix). Then it takes less time to display the top 10 movie recommendations. A snapshot of movie recommendations by system 2 can be seen below
